ll send the status update now, but I should double-check if this QLHV group session is actually supposed to be monitored.\\n\\nLooking back at the 16:15 report, the DTLX cron mentioned the QLHV ecosystem session was completed after about 3h 40m, and the math checks out—started around 12:25 UTC, ended around 16:05 UTC. So the session has been done for a while, but the status field is still showing \\\"running,\\\" which is stale.\\n\\nI'm realizing the cron:e7885813 session runs every 5 minutes and reports the current state to the direct session, so there's no need for me to send a separate report since that's already happening. But the instructions say to send the report directly to Lead via sessions_send, so I should do that anyway.\\n\\nFor the report content, I'll list the active sessions with their statuses: the two cron jobs are definitely running, the QLHV group session status is ambiguous but probably done, and the direct session is done. Now I'm calculating how long each cron session has been running to include in the report. So the 16:15 report is about 13 minutes old at 16:28. Since the cron runs every 5 minutes and the last one was at 16:15, I'm still within the expected window before the next scheduled report. I should go ahead and send the current status update now, including the two active cron sessions and noting that the QLHV group session has ended. I'm realizing the \\\"running\\\" status for that group session is stale since it's actually been ended since 16:09 UTC, and the DTLX cron already picked up on this state change at 16:15. So technically there's been a transition, but the current cron should handle reporting it naturally. I'll include the stale session in my report with a note about its actual status to make sure Lead is aware.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n              \"id\": \"call_function_38rizmb9a8yk_1\",\n              \"name\": \"sessions_send\",\n              \"arguments\": {\n        