{"type":"message","id":"7e645044","parentId":"5c4eeef6","timestamp":"2026-04-14T16:37:54.824Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me compare the current state against the saved heartbeat state.\n\n**Last known state (heartbeat-state.json):**\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` - running, 5p QLHV monitor\n- `cron:6f3323ef` - running, 5p DTLX monitor  \n- `cron:e7885813` - running, Agent Status to Lead, consecutiveErrors: 2\n- Pipeline: DEGRADED\n- Blockers: cron:e7885813 — 2 consecutive timeouts\n\n**Current state (sessions_list at 16:35 UTC):**\n\n\nLooking at the active sessions, I can see cron:ed2d0b5d and cron:6f3323ef are both running as expected, but the QLHV group session shows as done with an endedAt timestamp of 16:09 UTC. The Agent Status session is also running, and the main session appears to be done as well.\n\nI'm also seeing a few zombie sessions still lingering from previous runs, and there are some subagent sessions that have failed. But the critical change here is that the QLHV group session actually ended when it was supposed to—the DTLX monitor already caught this discrepancy at 16:15 UTC and flagged it as a stale session, so the previous heartbeat state was inaccurate about its status.\n\nNow I'm checking whether cron:e7885813 is still problematic. Looking at the latest run from about 4 minutes ago, it was sending reports to the direct session but hitting gateway timeouts. It appears to have finished running now with a status of \"running,\" which suggests it did complete despite the delivery issues. I need to recalculate the timestamps here. The current time is 16:35 UTC, and the session was last updated at 16:28 UTC—that's only about 7 minutes ago, not the 23 minutes I initially thought. So cron:e7885813 is actually still running and actively being used.\n\nThe real issue from the previous state was that cron:e7885813 had 2 consecutive timeouts when trying to deliver messages to the direct session, which is why the pipeline was showing as DEGRADED. But it looks like the subagent delivery itself eventually succeeded even though the gateway calls timed out, since the message did end up reaching the direct session.\n\nSo the question becomes: is this still a problem, or has it resolved? Looking at the current state, cron:e7885813 appears to be actively running with a recent updatedAt timestamp, so it might be attempting another delivery right now. The actual change worth noting is that the QLHV group session has transitioned from \"running\" to \"done,\" but the cron already flagged this at 16:15 UTC, so this is just a status update rather than a new issue. is 16:35 UTC. The 5p report at 16:30 did send a DEGRADED report. So this report at 16:35 should note any changes since 16:30.\n\nChanges since 16:30:\n- Same 2 cron sessions still running\n- No new failures\n- No new blockers\n- The QLHV group session state is unchanged (still done/stale)\n\nThe session status check shows cron:e7885813 is still running as of 16:28 UTC, about 7 minutes before the current time of 16:35 UTC, so it's definitely still active.\n\nThe QLHV group session ended around 16:09 UTC, and cron:e7885813 is now in its 4th+ minute of execution. The 16:30 report flagged the cron as DEGRADED due to 2 consecutive timeouts, but that might not be current anymore. However, I need to verify what cron:e7885813 is actually doing—it's labeled as \"Agent Status to Lead\" and appears to be sending messages to a direct session. Let me look more carefully at what it's been reporting.\n\nThe cron seems to be the one that sent the 16:30 DEGRADED report to the direct session, which delivered the status update showing two active sessions and flagging the QLHV group session as stale. Since the 16:30 report already covered this state, I should check whether anything meaningful has actually changed in the past five minutes before deciding to send another update.\n\nLooking at the current status at 16:35 UTC, the same two cron jobs are still running and the QLHV group session remains stale, so there's no new state change to report. However, I notice the QLHV group session status shows \"running\" in the heartbeat-state.json when it actually ended at 16:09 UTC—this stale status is a discrepancy worth flagging. This stale status was already noted in the 16:15 report, so it's not new—it's just persisting. The cron:e7885813 is still running and has been for about 23 minutes, but that's normal for a long-running process. Since nothing meaningful has changed in the last five minutes, I'll stay silent and update the heartbeat state with the current session statuses. I'm noting the session statuses have been stable for the past five minutes, and I'll update the heartbeat file to reflect the current state before staying silent.","thinkingSignature":"19723c908d9b46f884f735afd1b38f463b42fe31511e61eed257a0e601e0c8c4"},{"type":"text","text":"Comparing current state vs heartbeat-state.json:\n\n**Saved state (16:30):** `cron:e7885813` DEGRADED (2 timeouts), 3 sessions marked running, DEGRADED pipeline\n\n**Current state (16:35):**\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` ✅ running\n- `cron:6f3323ef` ✅ running\n- `cron:e7885813` ✅ running (recently active, no new errors detected)\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258` still showing stale \"running\" (ended 16:09 UTC — already noted at 16:15)\n- No new failures, no new blockers\n\nNo meaningful state change in the last 5 minutes. Silent exit.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hdd4xwsbel0u_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/memory/heartbeat-state.json","content":"{\n  \"lastChecked\": \"2026-04-14T16:35:00Z\",\n  \"sessions\": {\n    \"cron:ed2d0b5d\": { \"status\": \"running\", \"label\": \"5p QLHV monitor\", \"consecutiveErrors\": 0 },\n    \"cron:6f3323ef\": { \"status\": \"running\", \"label\": \"5p DTLX monitor\", \"consecutiveErrors\": 0 },\n    \"cron:e7885813\": { \"status\": \"running\", \"label\": \"A